  "prompt": "Is solving interview problems in sites like LeetCode better for interview preparation than solving problems in OJ?",
  "response": "Both LeetCode and traditional Online Judges (OJs) have their strengths in interview preparation. Let me break down the pros and cons:\n\nLeetCode Advantages:\n1. Interview-focused problem set\n- More aligned with actual tech interview questions\n- Problems categorized by company and difficulty\n- Covers common interview patterns and algorithms\n\n2. Better user experience\n- Clean, modern interface\n- Detailed solution explanations\n- Multiple solution approaches\n- Discussion forums\n- Company-specific problem sets\n\n3. Additional features\n- Mock interviews\n- Systematic problem-solving tracking\n- Premium features with curated content\n- Interview preparation guides\n\nTraditional OJ Advantages:\n1. Broader problem diversity\n- More academic and competitive programming problems\n- Complex algorithmic challenges\n- Broader range of difficulty levels\n\n2. Competitive programming focus\n- Often used in programming contests\n- More challenging optimization problems\n- Performance-critical solutions\n\n3. Multiple language support\n- Often supports more programming languages\n- More strict judging criteria\n\nRecommendation:\n- For interview prep: Primarily use LeetCode\n- For algorithmic depth: Supplement with traditional OJs (like Codeforces, SPOJ)\n\nBest approach:\n1. Focus on LeetCode for interview preparation\n2. Solve problems systematically\n3. Understand multiple solution approaches\n4. Practice time and space complexity optimization",
